When  using  software  rendering,  you  have  to  go  for  the  lowest
resolutions. The  603 is in  no way capable  of dealing with  this. In
fact,  the K6-II/400 is  also too  slow to  use software  rendering in
640x480, with a much faster CPU and a much faster bus... 

Hardware rendering is almost a requirement for low-end 603's.

> But here's a more serious point. In the first room (more I haven't tried as
> it's a little bit late) I made the figure hang in the air after I climbed up
> and went to the book and afterwards to the edge. There was no contact with
> the ground. I used the software renderer (at least I had configured the game
> like this). With hardware rendering this doesn't happen.
> See the private mail for a screen shot.

This thing isn't Amiga-Specific, in fact is is generally caused by low
frame rates. When the frame rate  drops (and this also goes for the PC
version), the "internal" updates are longer, so that not all obstacles
are correctly  identified. This will  not let you walk  through walls,
since you would  end up in a solid brush, but  things like the problem
you described are typical for that. 

The obvious solution is to use hardware rendering :)

Regards, Hans-Joerg.

